It is significant that at the sites where both
Cepaea species
were relatively recently introduced, the samples of
C. nemoralis
show greater phenotypic diversity. They also less often lack phenotypes (yellow unbanded) or traits (brown shells, ones with three lower bands), which are less common in Western Ukraine (Gural-Sverlova et al., 2021 b;
) as well as in other parts of Eastern Europe and in the present range of
C. nemoralis
as a whole (Gural-Sverlova et al., 2021 a;
). The absence of rarer forms in newly formed colonies may be due to a smaller number of founding individuals, to which we include not only adult and juvenile snails, but also eggs, which may be in the ground on the roots of seedlings. It is very likely that a greater number of planted seedlings âinfectedâ with
Cepaea
increases the likelihood of the formation of both a mixed colony of two species, and a
C. nemoralis
colony with a large variety of shell colouration.

